        <p>When firing at an opponent that is engaged in a melee, there is a chance of hitting the wrong target.</p>
        <p>There is a 5% chance of hitting an adjacent creature of a the same size or a size larger.  Roll your attack as normal, and then roll a 1d20, on a 1 the attack hits the adjacent target.  If more than one creature is adjacent to your target, multiply the chance to hit accordingly.</p>
        <p>Example:  Your party members (an elf rouge, and a human fighter) are engaged with a Hobgoblin and an Ogre.  The Elf is on the left side of the Hobgoblin, the Human in front of the Hobgoblin, and the Ogre is on the right side of the Hobgoblin. Your target, the Hobgoblin, is engaged in a melee with 3 other creatures.  Your chance to miss your target and hit a different creature is 15% (Medium Elf +5%, Medium Human +5%, Large Ogre +5%).  Roll a 1d20: 1 targets the Elf, 2 targets the Human, 3 targets ogre, 5-20 targets Hobgoblin (a hit depends on AC).</p>
        <p>Ignore creatures smaller than the targets size when calculating miss chance.</p>
