        <h1>Death and Unconsciousness</h1>
        <h2>Reduced to 0 HP</h2>
        <p>If you are reduced to 0 hit points during combat and are then brought back above 0 by any method other than a spell of level 1 or higher, gain 1 level of exhaustion.<br><br>
        These effects are cumulative, if you are brought back up by a healing potion, knocked unconscious again, then brought back up by another healing potion, you would have gained 2 levels of exhaustion.  If you would gain your 6<sup style="color: #a8a8a8;">th</sup> level of exhaustion in this manner, you are instead considered stabilized and will awake in 2d4 hours.  When you awake, you will have 4 levels of exhaustion remaining.<br><br>
        One level of exhaustion is removed after a long rest.</p>
        <h2>Death and Resurrection</h2>
        <p>If your character has died and is brought back within 60 seconds gain 2 levels of exhaustion.<br><br>
        These effects are cumulative, if your character dies again, and is revived within 60 seconds, you would incur 2 more levels of exhaustion.  If you would gain your 6<sup style="color: #a8a8a8;">th</sup> level of exhaustion in this manner, you are instead considered stabilized and will awake in 2d4 hours.  When you awake, you will have 4 levels of exhaustion remaining.<br><br></p>


