old <h2>Encumbrance</h2>
        <p>When using these rules, ignore the Strength column of the Armor table.<br><br>
        If you carry weight in excess of 10 times your Strength score, you are encumbered: Your base walking speed is reduced by 5 feet. Saving throws that use Strength, Dexterity, or Constitution are made with disadvantage.<br><br>
        If you carry weight in excess of 15 times your Strength score, you are instead over-encumbered: Your base walking speed is reduced by 15 feet. In addition, you have disadvantage on Ability Checks and Saving Throws that use Strength, Dexterity, or Constitution.<br><br>
        If you carry weight in excess of 20 times your Strength score, your base walking speed is reduced by 15 feet. In addition, any Ability Checks or Saving Throws that use Strength, Dexterity, or Constitution automatically fail, and all Attack Rolls are made with disadvantage.</p>

<p>All equipment must have a weight value.<br><br>When purchasing or using starting packs, break out each item and give it an appropriate weight value.</p>

Other intelligent races are known to exist but are rare or have little contact with the civilized world.<br><br><!--They are generally found in the wilder places of the continents.<br><br> *Roleplaying as one of these races will affect how people treat and react to you, the more “human/humanoid” you look, the more “normal” the reaction from the general populace. For instance, if you play a Hobgoblin and go into a northern village, you will most likely be met with fear and hostility. In the South you may be treated with wonder and disbelief. I am not trying to discourage you from playing a race, just be prepared from a roleplay point of view.*<br><br>-->


